1️⃣ Descendant Selector (parent child)
This selector targets all matching elements inside a parent, no matter how deeply nested they are.
                  Syntax
                  parent child {
                    property: value;
                  }
Example
                      <div class="container">
                        <p>This paragraph will be styled.</p>
                      
                        <div>
                          <p>This paragraph will also be styled.</p>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      
                      <p>This paragraph will NOT be styled.</p>

CSS
                      .container p {
                        color: red;
                      }
What happens
Both <p> elements inside .container become red.
The <p> outside .container stays unchanged.
Structure view:
                .container
                 ├─ p  ✔ styled
                 └─ div
                      └─ p  ✔ styled
So descendant selector affects ALL levels inside the parent.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2️⃣ Child Selector (parent > child)
This selector targets only direct children, not deeper nested elements.
Syntax
          parent > child {
            property: value;
          }
Example
                      <div class="container">
                        <p>This paragraph will be styled.</p>
                      
                        <div>
                          <p>This paragraph will NOT be styled.</p>
                        </div>
                      </div>
CSS
                    .container > p {
                      color: blue;
                    }
What happens
.container
 ├─ p  ✔ styled
 └─ div
      └─ p  ❌ not styled
Only the direct <p> child of .container gets the style.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3️⃣ Attribute Selector ([attribute="value"])
This selector targets elements based on their attributes.
Syntax
            element[attribute="value"] {
              property: value;
            }
Example
                  <input type="text" placeholder="Name">
                  <input type="password" placeholder="Password">
CSS
                  input[type="text"] {
                    border: 2px solid green;
                  }

Result
Only the text input gets the green border.
Password input remains unchanged.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1️⃣ :hover (Hover Pseudo-Class)
This selector applies styles when the mouse pointer is over an element.
Syntax
          selector:hover {
            property: value;
          }
Example
            button:hover {
              background-color: green;
              color: white;
            }
HTML
            <button>Click Me</button>

When you move the mouse over the button, the style changes.
Common uses:
button effects
link highlights
interactive menus


2️⃣ :nth-child() (Select Specific Child Elements)
This selector targets elements based on their position inside a parent.
Syntax:    element:nth-child(number)
Example
                <ul>
                  <li>Item 1</li>
                  <li>Item 2</li>
                  <li>Item 3</li>
                  <li>Item 4</li>
                </ul>
CSS
                li:nth-child(2) {
                  color: red;
                }
Only Item 2 becomes red.

You can also do patterns:
                li:nth-child(even) {
                  background: lightgray;
                }
This styles every even item.

Very common for:
table rows
lists
grids


3️⃣ * (Universal Selector)

This selector targets all elements on the page.
Syntax
          * {
            property: value;
          }
Example
          * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
          }
Developers often use this to reset browser default spacing.


4️⃣ + (Adjacent Sibling Selector)
This selector targets the immediate next sibling element.
Syntax
        element1 + element2
Example
          <h2>Title</h2>
          <p>Paragraph 1</p>
          <p>Paragraph 2</p>
CSS
            h2 + p {
              color: blue;
            }

Result:
Only Paragraph 1 becomes blue because it is the first paragraph after the h2.

Structure:
          h2
           └ p  ✔ styled
           └ p  ❌ not styled


5️⃣ ~ (General Sibling Selector)
This selector targets all siblings that come after an element.
Syntax
              element1 ~ element2
Example
              <h2>Title</h2>
              <p>Paragraph 1</p>
              <p>Paragraph 2</p>
              <p>Paragraph 3</p>
CSS
            h2 ~ p {
              color: green;
            }

Result: All paragraphs after the h2 become green.

Structure:
            h2
             ├ p ✔
             ├ p ✔
             └ p ✔
