1️⃣ Pseudo-Classes (:)
A pseudo-class styles an element based on its state, condition, or position.
Syntax
          selector:pseudo-class {
            property: value;
          }
Example
          a:hover {
            color: red;
          }
When the mouse hovers over the link, it becomes red.

Common Pseudo-Classes.....................................................................
:hover
Styles an element when the mouse pointer is over it.
                          button:hover {
                            background-color: lightblue;
                          }
:focus
Styles an element when it receives input focus.
                          input:focus {
                            border: 2px solid red;
                          }
Used for forms and accessibility.

:active
Applies when the element is being clicked.
                      button:active {
                        background-color: darkblue;
                      }

:first-child
Selects the first child of a parent.
                    li:first-child {
                      color: green;
                    }

:nth-child()
Selects elements based on their position.
                    li:nth-child(2) {
                      color: red;
                    }

You can also use patterns:
                    li:nth-child(even) {
                      background: lightgray;
                    }


2️⃣ Pseudo-Elements (::)
A pseudo-element styles specific parts of an element.
Syntax
                  selector::pseudo-element {
                    property: value;
                  }
Common Pseudo-Elements...................................................
::first-letter
Styles the first letter of text.
                p::first-letter {
                  font-size: 2em;
                  font-weight: bold;
                }
Often used in magazines or blogs.
Example effect:
This is a paragraph.

::first-line
Styles the first line of text.
                p::first-line {
                  font-weight: bold;
                }

::before
Inserts content before an element.
              h1::before {
                content: "★ ";
              }

HTML:
<h1>Title</h1>
Result:
★ Title


::after
Inserts content after an element.
              h1::after {
                content: " ✔";
              }

::selection
Styles text when the user highlights it.
                ::selection {
                  background: yellow;
                  color: black;
                }

